This article is a presidential proclamation by Barack Obama declaring July 27, 2013, as National Korean War Veterans Armistice Day. The proclamation recognizes the 60th anniversary of the end of the Korean War and pays tribute to the brave soldiers who fought in the conflict. It acknowledges their extraordinary courage and the sacrifices they made to defend a country they never knew and a people they never met. The proclamation emphasizes the importance of honoring these veterans not just with words, but with deeds, by providing resources to current troops, supporting veterans and their families, and continuing the search for missing and imprisoned soldiers. It also highlights the progress made in the Republic of Korea since the war, both economically and as a close ally of the United States. The proclamation concludes by calling upon all Americans to observe the day with appropriate ceremonies and activities to honor the Korean War veterans.